# SECTION 05 — FACT IDENTIFICATION RULES

## Fact Definition

Facts contain measurable events or measurable states.

---

## Fact Qualification Test

A table is a fact when it stores:

```text
Counts

Volumes

Quantities

Capacities

Utilization

Transactions

Snapshots

Performance Metrics
```

---

## Fact Characteristics

Facts must:

```text
Have Declared Grain

Contain Measurable Values

Contain Foreign Keys

Support Business Calculations

Relate To Dimensions
```

---

## Fact Naming Standards

Physical Layer

```text
Fact_Capacity

Fact_Occupancy

Fact_Confirmation
```

Business Layer

```text
Capacity

Occupancy

Confirmation
```

---

## Fact Design Rules

Facts should:

```text
Be Narrow

Be Additive Where Possible

Avoid Free Text

Avoid Commentary

Avoid Descriptive Attributes
```

---

## Fact Validation Test

A fact table should answer:

```text
What Happened?

How Many?

How Much?

How Often?
```

---

# SECTION 06 — DIMENSION IDENTIFICATION RULES

## Dimension Definition

Dimensions provide business context.

---

## Dimension Qualification Test

Users naturally ask:

```text
By Centre

By Region

By Date

By Animal Type

By Department
```

These are dimensions.

---

## Dimension Characteristics

Dimensions should contain:

```text
Names

Descriptions

Classifications

Hierarchies

Grouping Attributes
```

---

## Standard Shared Dimensions

```text
Dim_Date

Dim_Region

Dim_Centre

Dim_AnimalType

Dim_Location
```

---

## Dimension Rules

Dimensions must:

```text
Be Business Friendly

Support Filtering

Support Grouping

Support Drill Down
```

---

## Dimension Validation Test

A dimension should answer:

```text
Who?

What?

Where?

When?
```

---

# SECTION 07 — MEASURE DESIGN RULES

## Measure First Principle

Before building facts:

```text
Define Measures First
```

---

## Every Measure Must Define

```text
Measure Name

Business Definition

Decision Supported

Signal Supported

Threshold

Action

Visual Usage

Fact Source
```

---

## Example

Measure

```text
Remaining Capacity
```

Business Definition

```text
Available Care Capacity
```

Decision Supported

```text
Can this centre receive another animal?
```

---

## Explicit Measures Only

Always create explicit measures.

Avoid implicit aggregations.

---

## Measure Validation Test

Ask:

```text
What decision becomes easier because of this measure?
```

If no answer exists:

```text
The measure should not exist.
```

---

# SECTION 08 — RELATIONSHIP RULES

## Standard Relationship Pattern

```text
Dimension
      ↓
Fact
```

---

## Preferred Cardinality

```text
One-To-Many
```

---

## Avoid

```text
Many-To-Many
```

unless justified.

---

## Filter Direction

Default:

```text
Single Direction

Dimension → Fact
```

---

## Relationship Documentation

Every relationship must define:

```text
Parent

Child

Cardinality

Filter Direction

Business Purpose
```

---

# SECTION 09 — KIMBALL STANDARDS

## Star Schema First

Default architecture:

```text
Dimensions
      ↓
Fact
```

---

## Conformed Dimensions

Shared dimensions must be reused.

Examples:

```text
Date

Centre

Region
```

---

## Business-Focused Design

Model for:

```text
Analysis
```

not:

```text
Source System Convenience
```

---

## Grain Before Fact

Kimball Rule:

```text
Declare Grain First
```

Always.

---

